{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775891920427,"sessionID":"ses_284984126ffeSNmBADjiRS4L0q","part":{"id":"prt_d7b682c8a001gNRBTVs3ZKaRaQ","messageID":"msg_d7b67ff97001Fjfzt4RCprk2Xy","sessionID":"ses_284984126ffeSNmBADjiRS4L0q","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_functions.read:3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Specification: CLI Publish Command (AR-022)\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: **AR ID:** AR-022  \n6: **Module:** cmd/cli  \n7: **Language:** Python  \n8: **Size:** L  \n9: \n10: Provide the `publish` command for the AgentCube CLI to deploy packaged agents to Kubernetes using either AgentRuntime CR (via AgentCubeProvider) or standard Deployment/Service (via KubernetesProvider).\n11: \n12: ---\n13: \n14: ## Requirements\n15: \n16: ### Requirement: Publish command - CLI options and defaults\n17: \n18: The system SHALL provide a `publish` command via Typer with specified options and sensible defaults.\n19: \n20: #### Scenario: Default option values\n21: - **GIVEN** the user runs `agentcube publish` without any options\n22: - **WHEN** the command parses arguments\n23: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL use the following defaults:\n24:   - `workspace` = `\".\"` (current directory)\n25:   - `version` = `None`\n26:   - `image_url` = `None`\n27:   - `image_username` = `None`\n28:   - `image_password` = `None`\n29:   - `description` = `None`\n30:   - `region` = `None`\n31:   - `cloud_provider` = `None`\n32:   - `provider` = `\"agentcube\"`\n33:   - `node_port` = `None`\n34:   - `replicas` = `None`\n35:   - `namespace` = `None`\n36:   - `verbose` = `False`\n37: \n38: #### Scenario: Workspace path override\n39: - **GIVEN** the user specifies `-f /path/to/agent` or `--workspace /path/to/agent`\n40: - **WHEN** the publish command executes\n41: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL resolve the workspace to the provided path\n42: \n43: #### Scenario: Provider selection - AgentCube\n44: - **GIVEN** the user specifies `--provider agentcube`\n45: - **WHEN** the publish command executes\n46: - **THEN** the system SHALL use `AgentCubeProvider` to deploy the agent as an AgentRuntime CR\n47: \n48: #### Scenario: Provider selection - Kubernetes\n49: - **GIVEN** the user specifies `--provider k8s`\n50: - **WHEN** the publish command executes\n51: - **THEN** the system SHALL use `KubernetesProvider` to deploy the agent as a Deployment with NodePort Service\n52: \n53: ---\n54: \n55: ### Requirement: Publish command - metadata validation\n56: \n57: The system SHALL validate workspace metadata before attempting to publish.\n58: \n59: #### Scenario: Missing workspace directory\n60: - **GIVEN** the specified workspace path does not exist\n61: - **WHEN** `PublishRuntime.publish` is invoked\n62: - **THEN** the system SHALL raise `ValueError` with message indicating the directory does not exist\n63: \n64: #### Scenario: Missing agent_metadata.yaml\n65: - **GIVEN** the workspace exists but contains no `agent_metadata.yaml`, `agent.yaml`, or `metadata.yaml` file\n66: - **WHEN** metadata loading is attempted\n67: - **THEN** the system SHALL raise `FileNotFoundError` indicating the metadata file is missing\n68: \n69: #### Scenario: Invalid metadata schema\n70: - **GIVEN** the metadata file contains invalid fields (e.g., unsupported language, invalid port)\n71: - **WHEN** `MetadataService.load_metadata` parses the YAML\n72: - **THEN** Pydantic SHALL raise `ValidationError` with details about the invalid fields\n73: \n74: ---\n75: \n76: ### Requirement: Publish command - image preparation\n77: \n78: The system SHALL prepare a container image before deployment, supporting both local and cloud build modes.\n79: \n80: #### Scenario: Local build mode with existing image\n81: - **GIVEN** `build_mode` is `\"local\"` in metadata and a local Docker image exists for the agent\n82: - **WHEN** `_prepare_local_image` is called with `image_url`, `image_username`, and `image_password` provided\n83: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n84:   1. Tag the local image with the provided `image_url`\n85:   2. Login to the registry using credentials if provided\n86:   3. Push the image to the registry\n87:   4. Return the full image URL\n88: \n89: #### Scenario: Cloud build mode\n90: - **GIVEN** `build_mode` is `\"cloud\"` in metadata\n91: - **WHEN** `_prepare_cloud_image` is invoked\n92: - **THEN** the system SHALL return the image URL from metadata or options, skipping local Docker operations\n93: \n94: #### Scenario: Missing image_url in local mode\n95: - **GIVEN** `build_mode` is `\"local\"` and `image_url` is not provided in options or metadata\n96: - **WHEN** `_prepare_local_image` attempts to prepare the image\n97: - **THEN** the system SHALL raise `ValueError` indicating that `image_url` is required for local build mode\n98: \n99: #### Scenario: Docker unavailable in local mode\n100: - **GIVEN** `build_mode` is `\"local\"` and Docker daemon is not running\n101: - **WHEN** `DockerService.check_docker_available` is called\n102: - **THEN** it SHALL return `False` and `PublishRuntime` SHALL raise `RuntimeError(\"Docker is not available or not running\")`\n103: \n104: ---\n105: \n106: ### Requirement: Publish command - AgentCube provider deployment\n107: \n108: The system SHALL deploy agents as AgentRuntime CRs when using the `agentcube` provider.\n109: \n110: #### Scenario: AgentCube deployment with valid metadata\n111: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"agentcube\"` and metadata contains valid `agent_name`, `image` (with URL), `port`, and required readiness probe fields\n112: - **WHEN** `_publish_cr_to_k8s` is invoked\n113: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n114:   1. Call `AgentCubeProvider.deploy_agent_runtime` with the agent configuration\n115:   2. Include `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL` and `ROUTER_URL` from metadata or environment in `env_vars`\n116:   3. Set `sessionTimeout` to `\"15m\"` and `maxSessionDuration` to `\"8h\"`\n117:   4. Reference `imagePullSecrets` as `[{\"name\": \"default-secret\"}]`\n118:   5. Return deployment result with `agent_id`, `status`, and endpoint information\n119: \n120: #### Scenario: Missing required URLs for AgentCube\n121: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"agentcube\"` and metadata lacks both `router_url` and `workload_manager_url`\n122: - **WHEN** `_publish_cr_to_k8s` validates prerequisites\n123: - **THEN** the system SHALL raise `ValueError` with message requiring both fields in `agent_metadata.yaml`\n124: \n125: #### Scenario: AgentCube deployment - CR already exists\n126: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"agentcube\"` and an AgentRuntime CR with the same name already exists in the namespace\n127: - **WHEN** `AgentCubeProvider.deploy_agent_runtime` is called\n128: - **THEN** the system SHALL update (patch) the existing CR with the new configuration\n129: \n130: ---\n131: \n132: ### Requirement: Publish command - Kubernetes provider deployment\n133: \n134: The system SHALL deploy agents as standard Kubernetes Deployment and Service when using the `k8s` provider.\n135: \n136: #### Scenario: K8s deployment with valid metadata\n137: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"k8s\"`, Kubernetes client initializes successfully, and metadata contains valid configuration\n138: - **WHEN** `_publish_k8s` is invoked\n139: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n140:   1. Call `KubernetesProvider.deploy_agent` with agent name, image URL, port, entrypoint, replicas, and optional node_port\n141:   2. Create or patch a Kubernetes Deployment with the specified number of replicas\n142:   3. Create or patch a NodePort Service\n143:   4. Call `wait_for_deployment_ready` with timeout of 120 seconds\n144:   5. Return deployment result with `deployment_name`, `service_name`, `namespace`, `node_port`, and `service_url`\n145: \n146: #### Scenario: K8s deployment with custom node port\n147: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"k8s\"` and user specifies `--node-port 30080`\n148: - **WHEN** the deployment is created\n149: - **THEN** the NodePort Service SHALL use port 30080 (if available in range 30000-32767)\n150: \n151: #### Scenario: K8s deployment with multiple replicas\n152: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"k8s\"` and user specifies `--replicas 3`\n153: - **WHEN** the Deployment is created\n154: - **THEN** the system SHALL create a Deployment with 3 replicas\n155: \n156: #### Scenario: K8s deployment readiness timeout\n157: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"k8s\"` and the deployment fails to become ready within 120 seconds\n158: - **WHEN** `wait_for_deployment_ready` exceeds timeout\n159: - **THEN** the system SHALL raise `TimeoutError` and record the error status in metadata\n160: \n161: #### Scenario: K8s deployment in custom namespace\n162: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"k8s\"` and user specifies `--namespace production`\n163: - **WHEN** deployment is created\n164: - **THEN** the system SHALL create the Deployment and Service in the `production` namespace\n165: \n166: ---\n167: \n168: ### Requirement: Publish command - metadata updates\n169: \n170: The system SHALL update the workspace metadata after successful or failed publish operations.\n171: \n172: #### Scenario: Successful publish metadata update\n173: - **GIVEN** the publish operation completes successfully\n174: - **WHEN** `_update_publish_metadata` is called\n175: - **THEN** the system SHALL write to `agent_metadata.yaml` with:\n176:   - `agent_id` set to the deployed agent identifier\n177:   - `agent_endpoint` set to the service URL\n178:   - `k8s_deployment` containing deployment type (\"AgentRuntime\" or \"Deployment\"), name, and namespace\n179:   - `version` updated if a new version was specified\n180:   - `status` set to \"published\"\n181: \n182: #### Scenario: Failed publish metadata update\n183: - **GIVEN** the publish operation fails\n184: - **WHEN** the error is handled\n185: - **THEN** the system SHALL update metadata with `status` set to \"error\" and include error details\n186: \n187: ---\n188: \n189: ### Requirement: Publish command - error handling\n190: \n191: The system SHALL handle errors gracefully using the `_handle_error` pattern.\n192: \n193: #### Scenario: Error with verbose mode\n194: - **GIVEN** an exception occurs during publish and `--verbose` is enabled\n195: - **WHEN** the error is caught in the CLI command\n196: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n197:   1. Print \"Error publishing agent: {error message}\" in red\n198:   2. Print the full traceback\n199:   3. Exit with code 1 via `typer.Exit(1)`\n200: \n201: #### Scenario: Error without verbose mode\n202: - **GIVEN** an exception occurs during publish and `--verbose` is disabled\n203: - **WHEN** the error is caught in the CLI command\n204: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n205:   1. Print \"Error publishing agent: {error message}\" in red\n206:   2. Exit with code 1 via `typer.Exit(1)` without printing traceback\n207: \n208: #### Scenario: Kubernetes client initialization failure\n209: - **GIVEN** the Kubernetes client fails to initialize (e.g., no kubeconfig, invalid credentials)\n210: - **WHEN** `KubernetesProvider` or `AgentCubeProvider` is instantiated\n211: - **THEN** the system SHALL raise an appropriate exception that is propagated through `_handle_error`\n212: \n213: ---\n214: \n215: ### Requirement: Publish command - version management\n216: \n217: The system SHALL support explicit version specification for publishing.\n218: \n219: #### Scenario: Explicit version override\n220: - **GIVEN** the user specifies `--version v2.0.0`\n221: - **WHEN** the publish command executes\n222: - **THEN** the system SHALL update metadata with the specified version before deployment\n223: \n224: #### Scenario: Version from metadata\n225: - **GIVEN** the user does not specify `--version` but metadata contains a `version` field\n226: - **WHEN** the publish command executes\n227: - **THEN** the system SHALL use the version from metadata\n228: \n229: #### Scenario: No version specified\n230: - **GIVEN** neither `--version` option nor metadata `version` field is set\n231: - **WHEN** the publish command executes\n232: - **THEN** the system SHALL proceed without a version tag, using \"latest\" as default for image tagging\n233: \n234: ---\n235: \n236: ### Requirement: Publish command - region and cloud provider support\n237: \n238: The system SHALL support region and cloud provider configuration for cloud build scenarios.\n239: \n240: #### Scenario: Region specification\n241: - **GIVEN** the user specifies `--region us-east-1`\n242: - **WHEN** the publish command executes in cloud build mode\n243: - **THEN** the system SHALL include the region in deployment configuration\n244: \n245: #### Scenario: Cloud provider specification\n246: - **GIVEN** the user specifies `--cloud-provider huawei`\n247: - **WHEN** the publish command executes in cloud build mode\n248: - **THEN** the system SHALL use cloud provider-specific configuration for image building and deployment\n249: \n250: ---\n251: \n252: ### Requirement: Publish command - description override\n253: \n254: The system SHALL support overriding the agent description at publish time.\n255: \n256: #### Scenario: Description from CLI option\n257: - **GIVEN** the user specifies `--description \"My production agent\"`\n258: - **WHEN** the publish command executes\n259: - **THEN** the system SHALL use the provided description, overriding any description in metadata\n260: \n261: #### Scenario: Description from metadata\n262: - **GIVEN** the user does not specify `--description` and metadata contains a description\n263: - **WHEN** the publish command executes\n264: - **THEN** the system SHALL use the description from metadata\n265: \n266: ---\n267: \n268: ### Requirement: Publish command - image registry authentication\n269: \n270: The system SHALL support registry authentication for pushing images.\n271: \n272: #### Scenario: Registry authentication with credentials\n273: - **GIVEN** the user provides `--image-username myuser` and `--image-password mypass`\n274: - **WHEN** `_docker_login_sdk` is called\n275: - **THEN** the system SHALL authenticate with the registry using the provided credentials before pushing\n276: \n277: #### Scenario: Registry authentication without credentials\n278: - **GIVEN** no registry credentials are provided\n279: - **WHEN** the image push is attempted\n280: - **THEN** the system SHALL attempt to push without authentication (relying on existing Docker credentials or public registry)\n281: \n282: #### Scenario: Image URL with embedded credentials\n283: - **GIVEN** the `image_url` contains embedded credentials (e.g., `user:pass@registry.com/image`)\n284: - **WHEN** the image is prepared for publishing\n285: - **THEN** the system SHALL extract and use the credentials for registry authentication\n286: \n287: ---\n288: \n289: ## File Index\n290: \n291: | Path | Purpose |\n292: |------|---------|\n293: | `agentcube/cli/main.py` | Typer app with `publish` command definition |\n294: | `agentcube/runtime/publish_runtime.py` | `PublishRuntime` class with publish logic |\n295: | `agentcube/services/agentcube_provider.py` | `AgentCubeProvider` for AgentRuntime CR deployment |\n296: | `agentcube/services/k8s_provider.py` | `KubernetesProvider` for standard K8s Deployment/Service |\n297: | `agentcube/services/docker_service.py` | `DockerService` for image operations |\n298: | `agentcube/services/metadata_service.py` | `MetadataService` for metadata management |\n299: | `agentcube/models/pack_models.py` | `MetadataOptions` dataclass |\n300: \n301: ---\n302: \n303: ## Dependencies\n304: \n305: | Dependency | Purpose |\n306: |------------|---------|\n307: | `typer[all]>=0.9.0` | CLI framework |\n308: | `pydantic>=2.0.0` | Data validation for metadata |\n309: | `pyyaml>=6.0` | YAML parsing for metadata files |\n310: | `docker>=6.0.0` | Docker SDK for image operations |\n311: | `kubernetes>=28.0.0` | Kubernetes client (optional) |\n312: | `rich>=13.0.0` | Rich text output and progress indicators |\n313: \n314: ---\n315: \n316: ## CLI Usage Examples\n317: \n318: ```bash\n319: # Publish to AgentCube (default provider)\n320: agentcube publish -f ./my-agent\n321: \n322: # Publish to Kubernetes with custom settings\n323: agentcube publish -f ./my-agent --provider k8s --replicas 3 --node-port 30080\n324: \n325: # Publish with registry authentication\n326: agentcube publish -f ./my-agent --image-url registry.com/myimage:v1.0 \\\n327:   --image-username myuser --image-password mypass\n328: \n329: # Publish with version override\n330: agentcube publish -f ./my-agent --version v2.0.0\n331: \n332: # Publish to custom namespace\n333: agentcube publish -f ./my-agent --provider k8s --namespace production\n334: ```\n335: \n336: ---\n337: \n338: ## Integration Points\n339: \n340: | Component | Integration |\n341: |-----------|-------------|\n342: | `PackRuntime` | Uses metadata created during pack phase |\n343: | `BuildRuntime` | Uses images built during build phase |\n344: | `AgentCubeProvider` | Creates/updates AgentRuntime CRs in K8s |\n345: | `KubernetesProvider` | Creates Deployments and Services in K8s |\n346: | `DockerService` | Tags and pushes images to registries |\n347: | `MetadataService` | Loads and updates agent metadata |\n348: \n349: ---\n350: \n351: ## Notes\n352: \n353: - The `publish` command requires a packaged workspace with valid `agent_metadata.yaml`\n354: - For `provider=agentcube`, the metadata must include `router_url` and `workload_manager_url`\n355: - For `provider=k8s`, the Kubernetes client must have valid kubeconfig for cluster access\n356: - Image preparation depends on the `build_mode` specified in metadata (local vs cloud)\n357: - The command updates metadata with deployment information for use by `invoke` and `status` commands\n\n(End of file - total 357 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Delta Specification: CLI Publish Command (AR-022)\n\n## Overview\n\n**AR ID:** AR-022  \n**Module:** cmd/cli  \n**Language:** Python  \n**Size:** L  \n\nProvide the `publish` command for the AgentCube CLI to deploy packaged agents to Kubernetes using either AgentRuntime CR (via AgentCubeProvider) or standard Deployment/Service (via KubernetesProvider).\n\n---\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: Publish command - CLI options and defaults\n\nThe system SHALL provide a `publish` command via Typer with specified options and sensible defaults.\n\n#### Scenario: Default option values","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775891920412,"end":1775891920426}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775891920442,"sessionID":"ses_284984126ffeSNmBADjiRS4L0q","part":{"id":"prt_d7b683043001A4ZM9Zd3L3W036","messageID":"msg_d7b67ff97001Fjfzt4RCprk2Xy","sessionID":"ses_284984126ffeSNmBADjiRS4L0q","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_functions.read:4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-017/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-017/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-017: PicoD JWT 中间件 - Delta Specification\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: **AR ID:** AR-017  \n6: **Module:** `pkg/picod/jwt`  \n7: **Language:** Go  \n8: **Size:** S  \n9: **Base Spec:** AR-015 (PicoD 命令执行 API)\n10: \n11: The PicoD JWT Middleware provides authentication for PicoD API endpoints by validating JSON Web Tokens (JWT) on incoming requests. It supports HMAC (HS256) and RSA (RS256) signing algorithms.\n12: \n13: ---\n14: \n15: ## Requirements\n16: \n17: ### Requirement: JWT Token Validation\n18: \n19: The system SHALL validate JWT tokens from the Authorization header using configurable signing algorithms and claims.\n20: \n21: #### Scenario: Valid HS256 token passes validation\n22: - **GIVEN** a JWT token signed with HS256 and secret \"test-secret\"\n23: - **AND** `ValidationOptions{Algorithm: \"HS256\", Secret: []byte(\"test-secret\")}`\n24: - **WHEN** `ValidateToken(token)` is called\n25: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL verify the HMAC signature\n26: - **AND** return parsed `Claims` with no error\n27: \n28: #### Scenario: Valid RS256 token passes validation\n29: - **GIVEN** a JWT token signed with RS256 using a private key\n30: - **AND** the corresponding public key is configured\n31: - **AND** `ValidationOptions{Algorithm: \"RS256\", PublicKey: rsaPubKey}`\n32: - **WHEN** `ValidateToken(token)` is called\n33: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL verify the RSA signature\n34: - **AND** return parsed `Claims` with no error\n35: \n36: #### Scenario: Invalid signature returns error\n37: - **GIVEN** a JWT token with invalid signature\n38: - **WHEN** `ValidateToken(token)` is called\n39: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return `ErrInvalidSignature`\n40: \n41: #### Scenario: Expired token returns error\n42: - **GIVEN** a JWT token with `exp` claim in the past\n43: - **AND** no clock skew configured\n44: - **WHEN** `ValidateToken(token)` is called\n45: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return `ErrTokenExpired`\n46: \n47: #### Scenario: Clock skew allows near-expired tokens\n48: - **GIVEN** a JWT token expired 30 seconds ago\n49: - **AND** `ClockSkew: 1m` configured\n50: - **WHEN** `ValidateToken(token)` is called\n51: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL accept the token\n52: - **AND** return parsed `Claims` with no error\n53: \n54: #### Scenario: Wrong issuer returns error\n55: - **GIVEN** a JWT token with `iss: \"other-service\"`\n56: - **AND** `ExpectedIssuer: \"auth-service\"` configured\n57: - **WHEN** `ValidateToken(token)` is called\n58: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return `ErrInvalidIssuer`\n59: \n60: #### Scenario: Unsupported algorithm returns error\n61: - **GIVEN** a JWT token signed with ES256\n62: - **AND** `AllowedAlgorithms: [\"HS256\", \"RS256\"]` configured\n63: - **WHEN** `ValidateToken(token)` is called\n64: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return `ErrUnsupportedAlgorithm`\n65: \n66: ---\n67: \n68: ### Requirement: HTTP Middleware\n69: \n70: The system SHALL provide HTTP middleware that extracts and validates JWT tokens from requests.\n71: \n72: #### Scenario: Request with valid token proceeds to handler\n73: - **GIVEN** an HTTP request with `Authorization: Bearer <valid_token>`\n74: - **AND** JWTMiddleware is configured with valid validator\n75: - **WHEN** the request is processed\n76: - **THEN** the middleware SHALL extract the token\n77: - **AND** validate it successfully\n78: - **AND** call the wrapped handler\n79: \n80: #### Scenario: Request without token returns 401\n81: - **GIVEN** an HTTP request without Authorization header\n82: - **WHEN** the request is processed by JWTMiddleware\n83: - **THEN** the middleware SHALL return HTTP 401\n84: - **AND** body SHALL be `{\"error\": \"unauthorized\", \"message\": \"missing bearer token\"}`\n85: \n86: #### Scenario: Request with invalid token format returns 401\n87: - **GIVEN** an HTTP request with `Authorization: invalid_format`\n88: - **WHEN** the request is processed\n89: - **THEN** the middleware SHALL return HTTP 401\n90: - **AND** body SHALL be `{\"error\": \"unauthorized\", \"message\": \"invalid token format\"}`\n91: \n92: #### Scenario: Invalid signature returns 401\n93: - **GIVEN** an HTTP request with `Authorization: Bearer <bad_sig_token>`\n94: - **WHEN** the request is processed\n95: - **THEN** the middleware SHALL return HTTP 401\n96: - **AND** body SHALL be `{\"error\": \"unauthorized\", \"message\": \"invalid token signature\"}`\n97: \n98: #### Scenario: Expired token returns 401\n99: - **GIVEN** an HTTP request with expired JWT token\n100: - **WHEN** the request is processed\n101: - **THEN** the middleware SHALL return HTTP 401\n102: - **AND** body SHALL be `{\"error\": \"unauthorized\", \"message\": \"token expired\"}`\n103: \n104: #### Scenario: Invalid issuer returns 403\n105: - **GIVEN** an HTTP request with token from wrong issuer\n106: - **WHEN** the request is processed\n107: - **THEN** the middleware SHALL return HTTP 403\n108: - **AND** body SHALL be `{\"error\": \"forbidden\", \"message\": \"invalid issuer\"}`\n109: \n110: #### Scenario: Claims are added to request context\n111: - **GIVEN** a valid JWT token with claims\n112: - **AND** a request with `Authorization: Bearer <token>`\n113: - **WHEN** the wrapped handler is called\n114: - **THEN** the request context SHALL contain the parsed `Claims`\n115: - **AND** the handler can retrieve claims via `GetClaims(ctx)`\n116: \n117: ---\n118: \n119: ### Requirement: Configuration\n120: \n121: The system SHALL support configuration via environment variables.\n122: \n123: #### Scenario: HS256 configuration loads secret from env\n124: - **GIVEN** environment `PICOD_JWT_SECRET=my-secret`\n125: - **AND** `PICOD_JWT_ALG=HS256`\n126: - **WHEN** configuration is loaded\n127: - **THEN** the validator SHALL use HMAC with secret \"my-secret\"\n128: \n129: #### Scenario: RS256 configuration loads public key from file\n130: - **GIVEN** environment `PICOD_JWT_PUBLIC_KEY=/path/to/key.pem`\n131: - **AND** `PICOD_JWT_ALG=RS256`\n132: - **AND** a valid RSA public key file at that path\n133: - **WHEN** configuration is loaded\n134: - **THEN** the validator SHALL use the loaded RSA public key\n135: \n136: #### Scenario: Issuer is required configuration\n137: - **GIVEN** no `PICOD_JWT_ISSUER` environment variable\n138: - **WHEN** configuration is loaded\n139: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return an error\n140: - **AND** fail fast on startup\n141: \n142: #### Scenario: Clock skew configuration is parsed\n143: - **GIVEN** environment `PICOD_JWT_CLOCK_SKEW=2m`\n144: - **WHEN** configuration is loaded\n145: - **THEN** the validator SHALL allow 2 minutes of clock skew\n146: \n147: ---\n148: \n149: ## Changes to Base Specification\n150: \n151: This AR adds authentication middleware to AR-015 (PicoD 命令执行 API). No modifications to existing interfaces.\n152: \n153: ---\n154: \n155: ## New Interfaces\n156: \n157: ### JWTValidator Interface\n158: \n159: ```go\n160: package jwt\n161: \n162: import \"context\"\n163: \n164: // JWTValidator validates JWT tokens\n165: type JWTValidator interface {\n166:     ValidateToken(token string) (*Claims, error)\n167: }\n168: \n169: // Claims represents validated JWT claims\n170: type Claims struct {\n171:     Subject   string    `json:\"sub\"`\n172:     Issuer    string    `json:\"iss\"`\n173:     ExpiresAt time.Time `json:\"exp\"`\n174:     IssuedAt  time.Time `json:\"iat\"`\n175: }\n176: \n177: // ValidationOptions configures the validator\n178: type ValidationOptions struct {\n179:     Algorithm       string\n180:     Secret          []byte        // For HS256\n181:     PublicKey       *rsa.PublicKey // For RS256\n182:     ExpectedIssuer  string\n183:     ClockSkew       time.Duration\n184:     AllowedAlgs     []string\n185: }\n186: \n187: // NewValidator creates a JWTValidator with options\n188: func NewValidator(opts ValidationOptions) (JWTValidator, error)\n189: ```\n190: \n191: ### Middleware Function\n192: \n193: ```go\n194: // MiddlewareOptions configures the middleware behavior\n195: type MiddlewareOptions struct {\n196:     Validator    JWTValidator\n197:     ErrorHandler func(http.ResponseWriter, error)\n198: }\n199: \n200: // JWTMiddleware creates an HTTP middleware for JWT validation\n201: func JWTMiddleware(opts MiddlewareOptions) func(http.Handler) http.Handler\n202: \n203: // GetClaims retrieves validated claims from context\n204: func GetClaims(ctx context.Context) (*Claims, bool)\n205: ```\n206: \n207: ### Error Types\n208: \n209: ```go\n210: var (\n211:     ErrMissingToken         = errors.New(\"jwt: missing bearer token\")\n212:     ErrInvalidTokenFormat   = errors.New(\"jwt: invalid token format\")\n213:     ErrInvalidSignature     = errors.New(\"jwt: invalid signature\")\n214:     ErrTokenExpired         = errors.New(\"jwt: token expired\")\n215:     ErrInvalidIssuer        = errors.New(\"jwt: invalid issuer\")\n216:     ErrUnsupportedAlgorithm = errors.New(\"jwt: unsupported algorithm\")\n217: )\n218: ```\n219: \n220: ---\n221: \n222: ## Modified Interfaces\n223: \n224: None. This AR introduces new functionality without modifying existing interfaces.\n225: \n226: ---\n227: \n228: ## Behavioral Changes\n229: \n230: | Behavior | Before | After |\n231: |----------|--------|-------|\n232: | API authentication | None | JWT token validation required |\n233: | Request processing | Direct | Through middleware layer |\n234: | Error responses | Application-defined | Standardized auth errors |\n235: \n236: ---\n237: \n238: ## Dependencies\n239: \n240: | Dependency | Version | Purpose |\n241: |------------|---------|---------|\n242: | `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5` | v5.x | JWT parsing and validation |\n243: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/picod` | Local | Integration with AR-015 |\n244: \n245: ---\n246: \n247: ## File Index\n248: \n249: | Path | Purpose |\n250: |------|---------|\n251: | `pkg/picod/jwt/types.go` | Claims and options types |\n252: | `pkg/picod/jwt/validator.go` | JWTValidator implementation |\n253: | `pkg/picod/jwt/middleware.go` | HTTP middleware |\n254: | `pkg/picod/jwt/config.go` | Configuration loading |\n255: | `pkg/picod/jwt/errors.go` | Error definitions |\n256: | `pkg/picod/jwt/validator_test.go` | Unit tests |\n257: | `pkg/picod/jwt/middleware_test.go` | Middleware tests |\n258: \n259: ---\n260: \n261: ## Constants\n262: \n263: | Constant | Value | Description |\n264: |----------|-------|-------------|\n265: | `defaultClockSkew` | `1m` | Default clock skew tolerance |\n266: | `authorizationHeader` | `\"Authorization\"` | HTTP header name |\n267: | `bearerPrefix` | `\"Bearer \"` | Token prefix |\n268: \n269: ---\n270: \n271: ## Configuration\n272: \n273: ### Environment Variables\n274: \n275: | Variable | Required | Default | Description |\n276: |----------|----------|---------|-------------|\n277: | `PICOD_JWT_SECRET` | HS256 | - | HMAC secret for HS256 |\n278: | `PICOD_JWT_PUBLIC_KEY` | RS256 | - | Path to RSA public key PEM file |\n279: | `PICOD_JWT_ISSUER` | Yes | - | Expected issuer claim |\n280: | `PICOD_JWT_CLOCK_SKEW` | No | `1m` | Clock skew tolerance |\n281: | `PICOD_JWT_ALG` | No | `RS256` | Signing algorithm |\n282: \n283: ---\n284: \n285: ## API Endpoints Summary\n286: \n287: This AR provides middleware functionality; no new endpoints are exposed.\n288: \n289: ---\n290: \n291: ## Migration Notes\n292: \n293: - Add `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5` dependency to go.mod\n294: - Configure JWT environment variables before deployment\n295: - Apply middleware to protected routes using `JWTMiddleware(opts)`\n296: - Existing unauthenticated endpoints remain unaffected\n297: \n298: ---\n299: \n300: ## Acceptance Criteria Summary\n301: \n302: 1. **Token Validation**: HS256 and RS256 tokens validated correctly\n303: 2. **Claims Validation**: exp, iss claims validated with clock skew support\n304: 3. **Middleware**: HTTP middleware extracts and validates bearer tokens\n305: 4. **Error Responses**: Appropriate HTTP 401/403 responses for auth failures\n306: 5. **Configuration**: All settings configurable via environment variables\n307: 6. **Context Integration**: Parsed claims available via GetClaims(ctx)\n308: 7. **Unit Tests**: >85% coverage on validation logic\n309: 8. **Integration Tests**: End-to-end middleware flow tested\n\n(End of file - total 309 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-017: PicoD JWT 中间件 - Delta Specification\n\n## Overview\n\n**AR ID:** AR-017  \n**Module:** `pkg/picod/jwt`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** S  \n**Base Spec:** AR-015 (PicoD 命令执行 API)\n\nThe PicoD JWT Middleware provides authentication for PicoD API endpoints by validating JSON Web Tokens (JWT) on incoming requests. It supports HMAC (HS256) and RSA (RS256) signing algorithms.\n\n---\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: JWT Token Validation\n\nThe system SHALL validate JWT tokens from the Authorization header using configurable signing algorithms and claims.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-017/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775891920415,"end":1775891920439}}}}
